{"type":"message","id":"501f0500","parentId":"d5ed169d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T03:59:36.006Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_1ex5rdzdnmpf_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-23 235913\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: scripts/tic_analyzer.ps1 (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine the next concrete action.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- Pending items include:\r\n  1. Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n  2. Define significance scoring for pulse content\r\n  3. Tune λ empirically (start: λ=0.7)\r\n  4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  5. Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThe most actionable item based on the recent insights is the **TIC Experiment** (Temporal Invariance Compression):\r\n- Implement TIC classifier on `logs/pulse_*.md` files\r\n- Measure invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- Predict next pulse content from invariants\r\n- Validate against success criteria (>70%, >60%)\r\n\r\nThe key insight from this session is:\r\n> **COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY:** Causal structure IS invariant structure - compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation\r\n\r\nThis seems like the most concrete next step. I should:\r\n1. Look at the existing pulse logs to understand their structure\r\n2. Design a simple TIC classifier that can identify invariant vs variant content\r\n3. Test it against the success criteria\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist in the logs directory and understand the pulse log structure.\r\n\r\nActually, I should create a concrete implementation plan. Let me look at:\r\n- What pulse logs exist\r\n- Their format\r\n- Create a simple TIC classifier\r\n\r\nLet me write a concrete action to start the TIC experiment. I'll create a Python script that:\r\n1. Reads the pulse logs\r\n2. Extracts features that distinguish invariants from variants\r\n3. Makes predictions about next pulse content\r\n4. Validates against success criteria\r\n\r\nThis is specific, file-based, and advances the Phase 1 advancement goal.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight provides a concrete hypothesis to test: if I can classify pulse content as invariant vs variant and predict next pulse content, I validate that causal discovery and compression are the same problem. The TIC experiment is the most actionable next step.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a Python TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) classifier that reads recent pulse logs, identifies invariant vs variant patterns, and tests against the success criteria (>70% classification, >60% next-pulse prediction).\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 0\n- Completed at: 2026-03-23 23:59:27\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774324776005}}
